*Executive SummaryThis week, OSAC continued to make strong progress across
VMaaS, CaaS, and BMaaS, with five demos completed: the initial VMaaS flow
through the UI, the CaaS API, Public IP support, CaaS with automatic agent
provisioning, and VM status reporting from roles.Roadmap: details
<https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/11YIDvxTK940j4XgyainQO5yzA9a3ppVwy54oypo4eE0/edit?gid=552881355#gid=552881355>------------------------------This
Week's Demos (May 11, 2026)VMaaSVM Status reporting from roles (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/111xSwJU1GQYnkdHtJPH8AfqJ_AXbGonD/view>
53:40 - 1:00:32) - Added granular reasons and messages to VM status
conditions, making provisioning progress easier to understand without
checking controller logs.- Follow-up Actions- Apply the same granular
status reporting approach to CaaS and BMaaS.CaaSCaaS API (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/111xSwJU1GQYnkdHtJPH8AfqJ_AXbGonD/view>
0:40 - 5:30) - Introduced a cleaner CaaS API by moving common cluster
configuration from template parameters into explicit ClusterSpec fields.-
Added first-class fields for pull secret, SSH public key, release image,
and network settings such as pod CIDR and service CIDR.- Added dedicated
CLI flags for these fields, including file-based options for pull secret
and SSH public key.- The pull secret is write-only and redacted in API
responses.- The fulfillment service maps the new fields into the
ClusterOrder CR for the provisioning flow.CaaS with automatic agents
provisioning (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/111xSwJU1GQYnkdHtJPH8AfqJ_AXbGonD/view>
43:00 - 53:10) - Demonstrated CaaS using a file-based inventory and Metal³
for bare metal provisioning.- Showed how an AAP playbook reads the
inventory file and registers the servers as BareMetalHost resources.- The
servers were booted with the assisted discovery ISO and appeared as agents
for cluster installation.- A standard cluster template was then used to
start the cluster installation, which progressed successfully.- Follow-up
Actions- Add support for BCM and Carbide as inventory backends.- Integrate
the flow with the BareMetal API, including BareMetalPool and
HostLease.Cross-Cutting CapabilitiesPublic IP (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/111xSwJU1GQYnkdHtJPH8AfqJ_AXbGonD/view>
10:20 - 42:30) - Demonstrated the new Public IP management flow for
associating on-demand public IPs with resources, starting with
VM/ComputeInstance support. - Introduced two new resources: PublicIPPool
and PublicIP.- Showed the main personas:- Cloud Provider Admin creates the
PublicIPPool.- Tenant Admin allocates public IPs.- Tenant User attaches IPs
to owned resources.- Demonstrated the Public IP lifecycle: Pending →
Allocated → Attaching / Attached → back to Allocated after detach.- Showed
creation of a public IP pool, allocation of a public IP, attachment to a
demo VM, successful VM access through the public IP, detachment, and
cleanup.- Current implementation uses MetalLB Layer 2 as the backend
strategy.- Follow-up Actions - Replace the embedded ComputeInstance
reference with a dedicated PublicIPAttachment resource.- Discuss whether
Public IP attachment should be driven automatically from ComputeInstance
creation.- Extend Public IP support to CaaS and BMaaS.UIInitial VMaaS flow
(Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/1DZaT0UgdoYy1krIwJ5702i-Z4H8MGU6k/view?usp=drive_web>
1:10 - 15:30) - Demonstrated the initial OSAC UI experience with three
personas: Tenant User, Tenant Admin, and Cloud Provider Admin. - Focused on
the Tenant User flow, including the dashboard, VM status overview,
utilization trends, quotas, and recent activities.- Showed the My VMs page
with table/card views, filtering, VM details, and available VM actions such
as start, stop, restart, and clone.- Demonstrated VM creation flows.-
Showed the templates page with filtering by operating system and workload.-
The current UI is based on mocked data and not yet connected to the real
backend.- Follow-up Actions - Integrate the UI with the real backend and
live OSAC data.- Align UI terminology with backend concepts, including
replacing Templates with Catalogs if
agreed.------------------------------Upcoming Demos: - Optional dedicated
VM clusters - running VMs on a separate cluster instead of the main
management cluster.- Storage Tenant Onboarding - Provision per tenant
storage class on tenant creation.- Windows VMs - Add a VM template for
provisioning Windows-based virtual machines.- VAST Storage - Initial
implementation to enable CaaS with VAST storage, without yet integrating
with OSAC’s generic storage APIs.- Catalog Items - adds a user-facing layer
above Ansible templates, allowing providers to expose multiple curated
provisioning options that can reuse the same underlying Ansible role.- DPU
network class - Add support for tenant network isolation using
DPU/HBN-based networking.- Integration with BCM - Integrate with BCM as a
server inventory backend.- Admin APIs -Add administrative APIs for role
management, identity provider management, and project management.👉 Weekly
Demo Schedule: View Schedule
<https://docs.google.com/document/d/1V7uxuxJNyK2pkoaTQ3TJngnNp2ktvZzTAJMUESv0U4M/edit?tab=t.3nl8xrjatv13>------------------------------Blockers
and Risks - Inventory system integration - Today, inventory is file-based.
We need to add support for additional inventory systems, potentially
including BCM.- DPU/HBN hardware availability -  Integrating CaaS with
DPU/HBN is a high priority, but limited access to DPU hardware may slow
development and validation.- Netris - A request for a Netris license is
pending, so we can run Netris in our local environment and CI.Thanks,Alona.*

